Sure, here's a suggested roadmap for learning AI:

Mathematics and Statistics:

Linear Algebra
Multivariate Calculus
Probability Theory and Statistics
Optimization
Programming:

Python programming language
NumPy, SciPy, and Pandas libraries
Scikit-Learn for machine learning
Keras or TensorFlow for deep learning
Machine Learning:

Regression
Classification
Clustering
Dimensionality Reduction
Model Evaluation and Selection
Deep Learning:

Neural Networks
Convolutional Neural Networks
Recurrent Neural Networks
Autoencoders
Generative Adversarial Networks
Natural Language Processing:

Text Preprocessing
Word Embeddings
Recurrent Neural Networks for text classification
Sequence-to-Sequence models for machine translation
Computer Vision:

Image Preprocessing
Convolutional Neural Networks for image classification
Object Detection
Semantic Segmentation
Reinforcement Learning:

Markov Decision Processes
Q-Learning
Deep Q-Networks
Robotics:

Kinematics
Robot Control
Reinforcement Learning for Robotics
In addition to the above topics, it's also important to keep up-to-date with the latest research and advancements in the field by reading academic papers, attending conferences, and following industry leaders on social media.

There are many online resources available for learning AI, such as edX, Coursera, Udacity, and Fast.ai. You can also find many books and video courses on AI topics. It's recommended that you follow a structured course of study to ensure you cover all the necessary topics in a logical and progressive way. Good luck in your learning journey!
