Sure, here are some resources you can use to learn the topics I mentioned in the roadmap:

Mathematics and Statistics:

Linear Algebra: MIT OpenCourseWare's "Linear Algebra" course
Multivariate Calculus: MIT OpenCourseWare's "Multivariable Calculus" course
Probability Theory and Statistics: Harvard's "Statistics and Probability" course
Optimization: Stanford's "Convex Optimization" course
Programming:

Python programming language: Codecademy's "Learn Python" course
NumPy, SciPy, and Pandas libraries: DataCamp's "NumPy" and "Pandas" courses
Scikit-Learn for machine learning: DataCamp's "Scikit-Learn" course
Keras or TensorFlow for deep learning: TensorFlow's "Getting Started with TensorFlow" course
Machine Learning:

Regression: Andrew Ng's "Machine Learning" course on Coursera
Classification: Udacity's "Introduction to Machine Learning" course
Clustering: Stanford's "Machine Learning" course
Dimensionality Reduction: Stanford's "Machine Learning" course
Model Evaluation and Selection: Udacity's "Model Evaluation and Validation" course
Deep Learning:

Neural Networks: deeplearning.ai's "Neural Networks and Deep Learning" course on Coursera
Convolutional Neural Networks: deeplearning.ai's "Convolutional Neural Networks" course on Coursera
Recurrent Neural Networks: deeplearning.ai's "Sequence Models" course on Coursera
Autoencoders: Stanford's "Unsupervised Feature Learning and Deep Learning" course
Generative Adversarial Networks: MIT's "Generative Models" course
Natural Language Processing:

Text Preprocessing: Stanford's "Natural Language Processing with Deep Learning" course
Word Embeddings: deeplearning.ai's "Sequence Models" course on Coursera
Recurrent Neural Networks for text classification: deeplearning.ai's "Sequence Models" course on Coursera
Sequence-to-Sequence models for machine translation: Stanford's "Natural Language Processing with Deep Learning" course
Computer Vision:

Image Preprocessing: Stanford's "Convolutional Neural Networks for Visual Recognition" course
Convolutional Neural Networks for image classification: Stanford's "Convolutional Neural Networks for Visual Recognition" course
Object Detection: Stanford's "Convolutional Neural Networks for Visual Recognition" course
Semantic Segmentation: Stanford's "Convolutional Neural Networks for Visual Recognition" course
Reinforcement Learning:

Markov Decision Processes: David Silver's "Reinforcement Learning" course
Q-Learning: David Silver's "Reinforcement Learning" course
Deep Q-Networks: Udacity's "Deep Reinforcement Learning" course
Robotics:

Kinematics: MIT's "Robotics: Kinematics and Dynamics" course
Robot Control: MIT's "Robotics: Vision Intelligence and Machine Learning" course
Reinforcement Learning for Robotics: Berkeley's "Deep Reinforcement Learning for Robotics" course
These resources are just a starting point, and there are many more courses and tutorials available online for learning AI. It's important to choose the resources that work best for you and your learning style, and to stay up-to-date with the latest advancements in the field. Good luck in your learning journey!